Input.posts:
I don't have a feel for what lasting effects there would be for a galaxy that had a central quasar long ago, in its infancy. Would the huge flux deplete the central region? Retard star formation in the galaxy, or promote it? Other lasting effects? Is it known or thought that the quasar epoch would have predated early star formation in those galaxies? Or any evidence or thought that any quasars were slow to initiate, or long-lived coexisting with star formation and evolution in their galaxies? Are there any galaxies within 100 Mly that astrophysicists have reason to believe were quasars in their infancy? Is it known whether quasars also radiate neutrinos prodigiously? Some (maybe much?) of the infall into a quasar would have been dark matter. Do we know anything about how hot dark matter would radiate energy and how this might be discerned from quasars?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
The questions you are asking could easily fill an entire semester. Suffice to say that they are worthy of continued research, and in fact, are in the forefront of our studies of galactic evolution.

Title: Linking forum posts - analyze-9-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
The earth is 4.5 billion years old. The solar system is about that age. This seems to imply our galaxy was already a galaxy at that time, no ? So the light emitted by it 2.2 billion years ago was that of a normal galaxy, was it not ? I see three possibilities: - the solar system formed around a quasar, which 'disappeared' less than 2.2 billion years ago - 2.2 billion was a mistake and should have been something like 6 billion - I haven't understood what the professor was explaining Help please ? :)
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
The Hubble Space Telescope has shown that quasars are not isolated objects and even back then lay at the center of galaxies and are strongly linked to the supermassive black holes we see at the center of the majority of galaxies. One of the mysteries surrounding them is indeed why we see most supermassive black holes in our local neighborhood as dormant objects. There are some galaxies with active galactic nuclei, thought to be associated with SMBHs (such as M87), though none of these seems to have the power of, or shine as brightly as, quasars. Also, bear in mind that the 2.2 billion ly away 3C273 is the closest one we see, making it likely to be one of the last to see its activity fall off, at least in our part of the universe. Not all quasars would have seen this fall off at the same time of course. The transition to the current picture of the universe may well have been a long process - maybe the Milky Way's SMBH became dormant much earlier, if indeed it ever was a quasar.

Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
Since the furthest, and therefore the oldest, galaxies are moving away the fastest why do we conclude that the universe is accelerating in its expansion? It seems to me that since galaxies were moving faster in the past then the expansion would be slowing. Oh, and thanks for presenting this great course!
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
The situation is actually that the galaxies are moving faster in the present than in the past. That is actually a bit of a problem; why are we in the era when acceleration is 'rearing its head'? Whenever we put ourselves in a privileged position, either in space, or in time, we get into trouble, usually. Even though the far off supernovae are giving us the signature of acceleration, when you examine the implications, it means that NOW the Universe is accelerating, rather than before. To put it a bit more accurately, the component of mass-energy that is the acceleration, seems to be more observable now, as opposed to the past, when matter and radiation dominated the expansion.

Input.threadtitle: does the hubble constant allow parts of the universe to never be observed
Input.posts:
if the hubble constant - 71km/s per megaparsec then anything over 4225mpc is further away than a redshift =the speed of light. Since this is due to space expanding - not actual movement it is possible to have redshifts in excess of C? Any areas this far away we cant see. this works out as 12.6 billion years worth of expansion. so the oldest observable objects should be around this distance/redshift away from us. Does this stop the universe being older than this? Iin areas we cannot observe are just redshifted so far that the sapce in between us and them is expanding faster than any photon can ever travel.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
In short, there is some of the universe that we have not yet seen because not enough time has passed for light to have traversed the distance between it and us. For this reason, we define something called the 'observable universe' which, assuming the universe is isotropic (that is, the same in all directions), is a spherical volume with a radius of about 46 billion light years. The reason it is not 13.8 billion years (our latest best estimate for the age of the universe) is that the parts of the universe which appear at the very edge of what we can observe now reside much further away from us compared to when they sent out the light we see now - the expansion of spacetime itself has expanded the distance between us and that part of the universe. A number of reasons mean that some (if not the vast majority) of the universe is beyond this and currently invisible to us, including that the rate of the expansion of the universe is not constant and the proposed inflation of the very early universe, a very small fraction of a second after the big bang.

Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
The enormous luminosity of 3C273 was calculated assuming that its radiation was isotropic. Does not the clear jet in its image show that the assumption is wrong ? Was there a good reason to make this assumption ? How do we know that the radiation we measure is not the radiation of a narrow beam that happens to be in the direction of our planet ?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Certainly, the jet is not radiating isotropically. But the central engine appears to be. We see a lot of these jets coming from resolved objects, like M87, where the core radiation appears to be spherically symmetric.
Instructor's post : Certainly, the jet is not radiating isotropically. But the central engine appears to be. We see a lot of these jets coming from resolved objects, like M87, where the core radiation appears to be spherically symmetric.

Input.threadtitle: Does Hubble's law apply to quasars?
Input.posts:
Question from Lecture 2 of this week: Hubble's law was discovered as a property of galaxies. How do you know that it applies to quasars as well? For, if it doesn't, you cannot use the equation v = Hr to find the quasar's distance.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hubble's law may have been discovered by looking at distant galaxies, but it is a statement abut the expansion of the universe as a whole. We would expect it to hold for all distant objects, including quasars.
Instructor's post : Hubble's law may have been discovered by looking at distant galaxies, but it is a statement abut the expansion of the universe as a whole. We would expect it to hold for all distant objects, including quasars.
